<br>
Similarly, our past actions, or habits, make certain of our future behaviours more or less likely.  If you've been getting up at 5:30 A.M. every day for the last several years, you're not likely to wake up one morning and think, &quot;I'll sleep in till 7:00 today.&quot;  But it's possible.<br>
<br>
The main argument for free will, I think, is not an ontological one--since centuries of debate haven't settled the question on that level--but rather a practical moral one.  If we hold that all our thoughts and actions are absolutely predetermined, then in effect we're implying that there's no such thing as right or wrong behaviour.  But this is a counter-intuitive idea.  Even those faiths, such as Islam, which believe in complete determinism, have moral codes.  The alternative to a notion of ethics--secular or religious--would be a reversion to the &quot;nasty, brutish and short&quot; life of wild animals. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/25/03 3:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Free will vs. Determinism</span><hr size=1> I would like to believe in free will; I'll commit to that.  I am in fact a non-reductive determinist, i.e. I believe things have reducible elemental forms which, were they quantifiable, would allow us, with sufficient computing power, to predict the future absolutely.  Again, bear in mind that's a hypothesis based on educated speculation derived from mathematical intuition.  I'm skeptical enough to keep my margin of error healthy in that hypothesis.<br>
<br>
The axis of this debate occurs at the point where ambiguity begins, namely human ability to mathematically reduce anything into constituent, quantifiable elements.  Werner Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle which stipulates that the more precisely the position of something is determined, the less precisely the momentum is known, birthed quantum mechanics and threw philosophical determinism into a tizzy.  How can we measure something in its &quot;elemental&quot; state if the act of measurement alone compromises the integrity of the results?<br>
<br>
Another way of looking at things, if you'll go with this, is that humans are rhetorical &quot;actors&quot; whose linguistic acts shape their realities, thus language itself as the core of consciousness (consciousness or self-awareness increases or decreases according to linguistic skills, cross-species) is intimately involved in shaping our perceptions of things like fate, free will, determinism, and so on.  It's fascinating to me that part of the system, if it's a deterministic one, involves the eventual reflection by the results of the system (humans, for example) upon the system itself (the universe).<br>
<br>
As Carl Sagan was fond of poetically saying, we're all literally &quot;star-stuff.&quot;  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A> at: 10/25/03 3:18 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/25/03 3:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Free will vs. Determinism</span><hr size=1> Ashmodai, I agree with you completely.  In fact, it's Voltaire's primary argument in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Candide</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which was among other things his refutation of Netwonian contemporary and philosopher Gottfried Wilhelm von Leibnez.  Leibnez was famous for coming up with the idea (and phrase) that &quot;everything is for the best in this best of all possible worlds.&quot;  It quickly became an anthem for the excuse-makers.  If everything is for the best, then everything that happens -- be it perceived as good or ill -- is all for the best in the long run.  So why bother trying one way or the other?  Voltaire's response was appropriately scathing, though that's only one of several ways in which <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Candide</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> operates.<br>
<br>
The problem with accepting a purely deterministic system (it is also the problem with accepting a purely relativistic ethical system) is that volition and responsibility are annihilated.  Inasmuch as we hold to the belief that free will is possible, it seems to me that -- however ultimately &quot;caused&quot; -- we retain the ability to alter that equation, to send ripples down the time-stream. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wulfenbach>wulfenbach</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/29/03 7:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Free will vs. Determinism</span><hr size=1> I don't think free will makes sense.  There's determinism and there's chance.  You do things for a reason (though you may not know it) or randomly.  What else is there?  I'm a materialist, but I don't think assuming souls would really gain you anything.  You'd *still* either do things for reasons or randomly.<br>
<br>
It's of course possible to create a simplistic deterministic argument, such as genetic determinism, and refute that, but what does that show?<br>
<br>
Determinism doesn't erode morality at all, actually.  Like the old story of the thief before a judge: &quot;I couldn't help it, it was determined I would steal.&quot;  &quot;And it was determined that I would sentence you for it.&quot;  Our behavior is determined by our nature and environment, but that environment includes other people, and their expectations of us, and their responses to us.  By holding people to moral standards we increase the pressure on them to behave correctly.  On the other hand, determinism can give us greater understanding and sympathy for 'broken' people (like the mentally ill) who don't respond properly to the usual pressures, and call for different responses. <br>
<br>
But mostly you can justify the same overall behavior with free will or deterministic stories.  The former is more comforting.  The latter makes more scientific sense. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ashmodai@lucifer>Ashmodai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/29/03 10:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Free will vs. Determinism</span><hr size=1> Is doing something for a reason necessarily the same as being pre-determined by one's nature or environment to do it?<br>
<br>
That objection aside, Wulfenbach, I liked your example of the thief and the judge.  It reminds me of the story about the skeptic who challenged a Hindu teacher about his claim that the world is illusory.  &quot;If that's true,&quot;  the skeptic asked, &quot;what would you do if you saw a lion charging at you?&quot;  &quot;I would run,&quot; the teacher answered,  &quot;because the lion and I are part of the same illusion.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hg@lucifer>HG</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/30/03 12:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Free will vs. Determinism</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; You do things for a reason (though you may not know it) or randomly. What else is there?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The excluded middle.<br>
<br>
Why just either/or?  How about doing something 70% randomly and 30% for a reason?<br>
<br>
How does our reasoning process work, anyway?  Do we perhaps churn totally random thoughts in our minds, and then select the one that seems to make the most sense at the time?  In that case, do I act out of randomness (totally random thoughts) or for a reason (selecting the best one - perhaps totally deterministically, to add to the confusion)?<br>
<br>
And then physics: quantum mechanics tells us, how solid-looking objects and consistent behaviour arises from randomness at the quantum level.  (Flip 1,000,000,000 coins - 50% will be heads and 50% will be tails.)<br>
On the other hand, Chaos theory tells us, how chaos and randomness can arise from seemingly deterministic processes.<br>
<br>
So where can we draw the line between random and non-random?<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wulfenbach>wulfenbach</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/31/03 2:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Free will vs. Determinism</span><hr size=1> &gt;  Is doing something for a reason necessarily the same as being pre-determined by one's nature or environment to do it?<br>
<br>
Determined by one's nature *and* the environment.  And in a Newtonian or Laplacian universe, with no real randomness, everything would be pre-determined.  But that's not the same as &quot;pre-determined by one's genes&quot; or by one's nature.  Pre-determined by the initial conditions of everything and the natural laws.<br>
<br>
These days, there's more randomness in our physics.  But is that choice?<br>
<br>
&gt; Why just either/or? How about doing something 70% randomly and 30% for a reason?<br>
<br>
Fine.  Is that free will?<br>
I don't care about where the line between random and reasons is.  I care about &quot;free will&quot; as something real (as opposed to our feeling of ignorance of what we'll do next) being incoherent and undefined.<br>
