This hits the nail on the head, I think.  Yes, I believe that's the present location of debate.  It is very difficult however to prove uniformly to one or the other, since as Heisenberg illustrated, to measure is to change, and assuming a scientific approach (which I do) to be unable thus to measure according to the method's standards of proof creates the paradox which throws wide the door of ambiguity rather than narrowing the crack.<br>
<br>
I stand with the camp (Hawking for example) that hypothesize a grand unified theory of quantum gravity is possible, equally capable of defining (with sufficient computing power) our futures according to the measurement of all of the forces in play.  The other camp focuses on that seemingly random effect of measurement at the quantum level, but as you point out wulfenbach, is randomness really free choice?  As we're seeing even in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Lucifer</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, freedom (perceived or real) seems to rely upon certain organizing principles.  As you move closer to randomness (tantamount to chaos) those organizing principles are defeated by chance and freedom becomes less and less a function of measurable responses to stimuli.<br>
<br>
You could, I suppose, make the argument that free will walks some fine balancing act between chaos and order (which would line it up nicely with certain philosophies from antiquity).  Perhaps two interdimensional levels of activity occurring simultaneously, or if you want to really head out there, consider physicist Julian Barbour's <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.discover.com/issues/dec-00/cover/" target="top">recent arguments</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> that time is symptomatic only, that it doesn't exist at all, and that our progression through what we perceive as time is merely a cataloguing of snapshot existences.<br>
<br>
